<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="101" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,310,1732,1758]" box="[189,310,1732,1758]" pageId="33" pageNumber="101">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1732,1758]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="101" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1732,1758]" pageId="33" pageNumber="101">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,1779,1877]" pageId="33" pageNumber="101">
Epigyne of the new species is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="L. Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[815,949,1779,1806]" class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Sosticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loricatus">
<emphasis box="[815,949,1779,1806]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="101">S. loricatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs by the shape of atrium and the copulatory ducts: atrium triangular, wider posteriorly (vs wider anteriorly) and the ducts converge medially and diverge anteriorly (vs opposite).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="101" type="etymology">
